HW3 Exercise 1

Design an algorithm to simulate from a Geometric(p) (where x is the number of failures until the first success) distribution via the inverse transform method. (Hint: Recall that Geometric random variables are just the number of Bernoulli random variables with the same parameter p until you get a success. So just focus on simulating n Bernoulli variables and then you can transform to Geometric ones.)

What is x value if simulated Bernoulli trials are:

0 0 1: x=2

1: x=0

0 0 0 0 0 1: x=5

ALG

Step1: Sample Bernoulli data points, and stop once reach the first 1. (Inverse CDF method for Bernoulli distribution)

Step2: Count how many 0s before the first 1, set this equals to x.

Step3: Repeat Step1 and 2 n times to have n sample points from Geometric distribution

How to use inverse CDF method to generate Bernoulli sample: 

set.seed(3)
geo <- function(n, p){
  sample <- c() #An empty vector for our results
  for(i in 1:n){
      u <- runif(1)
      j <- 0 #Counter; so far, there have been 0 failures
      while(u>p){
        u <- runif(1)
        j <- j+1
      }
      sample[i] <- j #The number of trials it took to get a success
  }
  return(sample)
}

sample <- geo(1000,0.4)
mean(sample)
## [1] 1.551

Theoretical value: \(\frac{1-p}{p}=\frac{0.6}{0.4}=1.5\)

Bayesian analysis using MC integration

Bayes’ Theorem

Focus on modeling, assume data was generated from a statistical model, with model parameters are random instead of fixed.

\[p(\theta|x)=\frac{p(x|\theta)p(\theta)}{p(x)}\propto p(x|\theta)p(\theta) \quad\left(P(A|B)=\frac{P(A \cap B)}{P(B)}\right)\] where

  • \(p(\theta|x)\): posterior
  • \(p(x|\theta)\): likelihood or model, also denote as \(f(x|\theta)\) or \(L(\theta|x)\)
  • \(p(\theta)\): prior (normally denote as \(\pi(\theta)\) in Bayesian analysis)
  • \(p(x)=\int p(x|\theta)p(\theta) d\theta\) marginal liklihood of data

Prior

Conjugate Prior

A conjugate prior is a family of probability distribution such that the posterior distribution is the same family of probability as the prior distribution.

Ex. Suppose \(X_1,\ldots,X_n\) are \(n\) independent and identical distributed (i.i.d.) R.V.s from \(N(\mu,\sigma^2)\), each having an umknown mean \(\mu\) and known variance \(\sigma^2\). Assume the prior for \(\mu\) follows a normal distribution \(N(m,C)\), where the prior mean \(m\) and variance \(C\) are known. What is the posterior mean for \(\mu\) (\(E[\mu|\mathbf{x}]\))?

Based on question, Likihood is \[p(\mathbf{x}|\mu)=p(X_1=x_1,...X_n=x_n|\mu)=\prod_{i=1}^n\{\frac{1}{\sqrt{2\pi\sigma^2}}e^{-\frac{1}{2\sigma^2}(x_i-\mu)^2}\}\] The prior is \[\pi(\mu)=\frac{1}{\sqrt{2\pi C}}e^{-\frac{1}{2C}(\mu-m)^2}\] Then, by Bayes’ Theorem

\[\begin{align} p(\mu|\mathbf{x}) &\propto p(\mathbf{x}|\mu)\pi(\mu)\\ &= \prod_{i=1}^n\left\{\frac{1}{\sqrt{2\pi\sigma^2}}e^{-\frac{1}{2\sigma^2}(x_i-\mu)^2}\right\} \frac{1}{\sqrt{2\pi C}}e^{-\frac{1}{2C}(\mu-m)^2}\\ &\propto e^{-\frac{1}{2\sigma^2}\sum_{i=1}^n(x_i-\mu)^2}e^{-\frac{1}{2C}(\mu-m)^2}\\ &= exp\left\{-\frac{1}{2\sigma^2}(\sum_{i=1}^n x_i^2-2\mu\sum_{i=1}^n x_i+n\mu^2)-\frac{1}{2C}(\mu^2-2\mu m+m^2)\right\}\\ &\propto exp\left\{-\frac{1}{2\sigma^2}(-2\mu\sum_{i=1}^n x_i+n\mu^2)-\frac{1}{2C}(\mu^2-2\mu m)\right\}\\ &= exp\left\{-\frac{1}{2\sigma^2C}\left((nC+\sigma^2)\mu^2-2(nC\bar{x}+\sigma^2m)\mu\right)\right\}\\ &\propto exp\left\{-\frac{1}{2 \frac{\sigma^2C}{nC+\sigma^2}}\left(\mu-\frac{nC\bar{x}+\sigma^2m}{nC+\sigma^2}\right)^2\right\} \end{align}\]

This is proportional to Normal distribution, thus, \(\mu|\mathbf{x}\sim N(m_n,C_n)\) where \[m_n = E[\mu|\mathbf{x}]=\frac{nC\bar{x}+\sigma^2m}{nC+\sigma^2}=\frac{C}{C+\sigma^2/n}\bar{x}+\frac{\sigma^2/n}{C+\sigma^2/n}m\] weighted average of data and believe, and \[C_n=\frac{\sigma^2C}{nC+\sigma^2}=(\frac{n}{\sigma^2}+\frac{1}{C_0})^{-1}\]

Subjective Prior vs. Objective Prior

Subjective Bayes emphasize the use of a subjective prior, and statisticians should sit down with a domian expert to elicit an appropriate prior for the study.

Objective Bayes uses the objective/default prior, such that the inference is (at least) not biased. (Bayes and Laplace are the earliest scholars to consider objectivity in Byesian study.)

HW4 Exercise 3

Suppose \(X_1,\ldots,X_n\) are \(n\) independent and identical distributed random variables from \(Exp(\theta)\), where \(\theta\) is the unknown parameter. So, \[f(x|\theta) = \theta \; e^{-\theta x}, \quad x \ge 0.\]

We assume the prior distribution on \(\theta\) is the Gamma distribution (\(Gamma(3,2)\)). \[ g(\theta) = 4 \theta^2 e^{-2\theta}, \quad x \ge 0. \]

a). Write down the posterior distribution of \(\theta\), \(g(\theta|X)\).

Liklihood is \[f(\mathbf{x}|\theta)=f(X_1=x_1,...X_n=x_n|\theta)=\prod_{i=1}^n\theta e^{-\theta x_i}=\theta^ne^{-\theta\sum_{i=1}^nx_i}\]

Then, by Bayes’ Theorem

\[\begin{align} g(\theta|\mathbf{x}) &\propto f(\mathbf{x}|\theta)g(\theta)\\ &=\theta^ne^{-\theta\sum_{i=1}^nx_i}4 \theta^2 e^{-2\theta}\\ &\propto \theta^{n+2}e^{-\theta(2+\sum_{i=1}^nx_i)} \end{align}\]

This is proportional to a Gamma distribution, thus \(\theta|\mathbf{x} \sim Gamma(n+3,2+\sum_{i=1}^nx_i)\), and \[g(\theta|\mathbf{x})=\frac{(2+\sum_{i=1}^nx_i)^{n+3}}{\Gamma(n+3)}\theta^{n+2}e^{-\theta(2+\sum_{i=1}^nx_i)}\]

b). Suppose \(n=6\) and we observe that \(x_1=0.4, x_2=1.1, x_3=0.2, x_4=1.6, x_5=1.4, x_6=0.9\). Estimate the posterior mean of \(\theta\).

Since know \(\theta|\mathbf{x} \sim Gamma(n+3,2+\sum_{i=1}^nx_i)=Gamma(9,7.6)\), then \(E[\theta|\mathbf{x}]=\frac{9}{7.6}=1.184\)

Now for MC approach:

Case 1: can recognize the posterior distribution (& easy to sample from)

\(E[\theta|\mathbf{x}]=\int\theta g(\theta|\mathbf{x})d\theta\)

set.seed(3)
m <- 10000 
theta <- rgamma(m,9,7.6) 
mean(theta)
## [1] 1.183651

Case 2: can’t recognize the posterior distribution (/not easy to sample from)

\(E[\theta|\mathbf{x}]=\int\theta g(\theta|\mathbf{x})d\theta=\frac{\int \theta f(\mathbf{x}|\theta)g(\theta)d\theta}{\int f(\mathbf{x}|\theta)g(\theta)d\theta}\)

set.seed(3)
m <- 10000                            
x <- c(0.4, 1.1, 0.2, 1.6, 1.4, 0.9) # observed data
n = length(x)

theta <- rgamma(m,3,2)             # theta from prior distribution
f <- (theta^n)*exp(-theta*sum(x))  # compute the likelihood function

post.mean <- mean(theta*f)/mean(f) # estimate the posterior mean
post.mean
## [1] 1.187654

c). Suppose \(n=6\) and we observe that \(x_1=0.4, x_2=1.1, x_3=0.2, x_4=1.6, x_5=1.4, x_6=0.9\). 1) Design an acceptance-rejection sampling algorithm to generate \(10000\) (accepted) samples of \(\theta\) from the posterior distribution of \(\theta\). Use \(g(\theta)\) as proposal distribution. 2) Implement your acceptance-rejection sampling algorithm with R code. Plot the histogram of your generated sample.

Steps for A-R Method: (For this example target distribution is \(g(\theta|\mathbf{x})\) and proposal distribution is \(g(\theta)\))

  1. Find M: since \(g(\theta|\mathbf{x}) \propto f(\mathbf{x}|\theta)g(\theta)\), then \(M=sup_{\theta}\frac{g(\theta|\mathbf{x})}{g(\theta)}=sup_{\theta}f(\mathbf{x}|\theta)\)
  2. Draw a sample point \(\theta\) from prior(proposal) distribution \(g(\theta)\)
  3. Generate a random number \(u \in[0,1]\)
  4. Decide whether accept \(\theta\) from step 1 as a sample point from \(g(\theta|\mathbf{x})\) by checking condition \(u<\frac{f(\mathbf{x}|\theta)}{M}\); Yes—accept, No—reject
  5. Repeat steps 2-3 until have enough sample
set.seed(3)
N = 10000 
i = 1
sample= c()

likelihood <- function(theta){theta^n * exp(-theta*sum(x))}
M = optimize(likelihood, c(0,5), maximum = TRUE)$objective

while(i <= N){
  theta = rgamma(1,3,2)
  u = runif(1)
  if(u < likelihood(theta)/M){
    sample[i] = theta
    i=i+1
  }
}
hist(sample)

mean(sample)
## [1] 1.181786

MC for hypothesis test

Suppose that we wish to test a hypothesis concerning a parameter hat lies in a parameter space \(\Theta\). The hypotheses of interest are \[H_0: \theta \in \Theta_0 \quad vs \quad H_1: \theta \in \Theta_1\] Two types of error can occur:

  • Type I error: if the null hypothesis is rejected when in fact the null hypothesis is true. \(P(\text{reject }H_0| H_0 \text{ is true})\)
  • Type II error: if the null hypothesis is not rejected when in fact the null hypothesis is false. \(P(\text{doesn't reject }H_0| H_1 \text{ is true})\)

Power of a Test

Power function \(\pi: \Theta \rightarrow [0,1]\), which is the probability \(\pi(\theta)\) of rejecting \(H_0\) given that the true value of the parameter is \(\theta\).

The power of a test is the probability of correctly rejecting the null hypothesis, \(P(\text{reject }H_0| H_1 \text{ is true})=\pi(\theta_1)\).

Thus, for a given \(\theta \in \Theta_1\), the prob. of Type II error is \(1-\pi(\theta_1)\). Ideally, we would prefer a test with low prob. of error. Since Type I error is controlled by the significance level \(\alpha\), then comparing tests for the same hypotheses at same significance level, we are interested in comparing power of the tests.

MC estimate of the power of a test:

Step1: Select a particular value of the parameter \(\theta \in \Theta_1\).

Step2: Generate random sample \(x_1,\dots,x_n\) under the conditions of the alternative \(\theta_1\).

Step3: Compute the test statistic from the sample.

Step4: Record the test decision: set \(I = 1\) if \(H_0\) is rejected at significance level \(\alpha\), and otherwise set \(I = 0\).

Step5: Repeat Step 1-4 for total m \(\theta \in \Theta_1\), and compute the proportion of significant tests \(\pi(\theta_1) =\frac{1}{m}\sum_{j=1}^m I_j\)

HW4 Exercise 5

Plot the empirical power curve for the t-test in Example 6.9, changing the alternative hypothesis to \(H_1:\mu \neq 500\), and keeping the significance level \(\alpha = 0.05\).

Suppose that \(X_1,\ldots,X_{20}\) is a random sample from a \(N(\mu,\sigma^2)\) distribution, \(\sigma=100\). Test \(H_0 : \mu = 500 \quad H_1 : \mu > 500 \text{ at } \alpha = 0.05\). Under the null hypothesis, \[T^* = \frac{\bar{X}-500}{S/\sqrt{20}}\sim t(19)\] where t(19) denotes the Student t distribution with 19 degrees of freedom.

Step1: Select a particular value of the parameter \(\theta \in \Theta_1\), i.e \(\mu \neq 500\).

Step2: Generate random sample \(x_1,\dots,x_{20}\) under the conditions of the alternative \(\mu_1\).

Step3: Compute the test statistic from the sample.

Step4: Record the test decision: set \(I = 1\) if \(H_0\) is rejected at significance level \(\alpha\), and otherwise set \(I = 0\).

Step5: Repeat Step 1-4 for \(m=1000\) times, and compute the proportion of significant tests \(\pi(\mu_1) =\frac{1}{1000}\sum_{j=1}^{1000} I_j\)

n <- 20
m <- 1000  #number of replicates
mu0 <- 500 
sigma <- 100
mu <- c(seq(350, 650, 10)) #Alternatives Space 
M <- length(mu)
power <- c()
for (i in 1:M){
  mu1 <- mu[i]
  pvalues <- replicate(m, expr = {
    #simulate under alternative mu1
    x <- rnorm(n, mean = mu1, sd = sigma)
    ttest <- t.test(x,
    alternative = "two.sided", mu = mu0)
    ttest$p.value })
  power[i] <- mean(pvalues <= .05) # P-value less than sig. level, reject null
}
plot(mu, power, main="The power curve", xlab=bquote(mu), ylab="Power")
abline(v = mu0, lty = 1)
abline(h = .05, lty = 1)
